"1. Use LensKit 0.14.4 as the recommender framework and ensure all algorithm construction, training, recommendation, and evaluation APIs are compatible with that exact version.\n2. Load the three raw files from the working directory using these exact filenames: u.data (MovieLens100K), VideoGames.csv (Amazon Video Games), and UserTaggedArtists-timestamps.dat (Last.FM).\n3. Parse each dataset into a unified interaction table with at least user, item, and timestamp columns where available; preserve original IDs without accidental reindexing collisions across datasets.\n4. Apply 5-core filtering independently to each dataset so that every retained user and every retained item has at least 5 interactions after preprocessing converges.\n5. For MovieLens100K and Amazon Video Games, convert explicit ratings to implicit feedback by retaining only interactions with rating > 3 and dropping all others before 5-core filtering.\n6. Treat Last.FM as implicit feedback directly, using user\u2013artist interactions derived from the tagging data and removing duplicate user-item events appropriately for implicit recommendation evaluation.\n7. After implicit conversion and deduplication, represent interactions as binary feedback for model training and evaluation; do not use rating values as relevance weights.\n8. Generate exactly 5 different random seeds for data splitting and use the same seed set across all datasets and algorithms.\n9. For each dataset and seed, create a user-based 80/20 holdout split so every eligible user contributes interactions to both train and test when possible; implement logic to avoid empty test sets or dropping users silently.\n10. Use the identical split for all three algorithms within a given dataset-seed condition to ensure fair comparison.\n11. Train exactly these three recommenders on each split: ALS, ItemKNN, and Pop.\n12. Use standard/default LensKit hyperparameters for each algorithm unless a parameter must be set explicitly for implicit data compatibility; document any such required settings in the code.\n13. Fit each model only on the training interactions from its split, with no leakage of held-out interactions into training, candidate generation, or popularity statistics.\n14. Generate top-N recommendations per test user from items not seen in that user\u2019s training history only.\n15. Evaluate each algorithm, dataset, and seed using nDCG@1, nDCG@5, nDCG@10, Precision@1, Precision@5, and Precision@10.\n16. Compute metrics at the user level and then aggregate to per-condition means; record the number of evaluated users for each condition.\n17. Store results in a tidy tabular format containing at least dataset, algorithm, seed, metric, k, value, and evaluated_user_count.\n18. Include robust handling for users with too few interactions to support an 80/20 split after preprocessing, with an explicit policy that is implemented consistently and reported.\n19. Ensure evaluation is reproducible by fixing all relevant random states, including split generation and any algorithm training randomness.\n20. Perform a short statistical analysis quantifying seed sensitivity, including at minimum the mean, standard deviation, and coefficient of variation of each metric across the 5 seeds for every dataset-algorithm-k combination.\n21. Add a comparative statistical test or variance analysis across seeds that is valid for repeated runs on identical configurations (e.g., repeated-measures or nonparametric paired comparison where appropriate) and report effect sizes or practical variability, not just p-values.\n22. Output concise summary tables highlighting how much accuracy varies with random seed for each algorithm and dataset, and identify the most and least seed-sensitive settings.\n23. Save all intermediate and final results to disk so the experiment can be rerun without losing split definitions or metric outputs.\n24. Include validation checks that confirm preprocessing counts, 5-core satisfaction, split proportions, and metric computation complete without errors on all three datasets."